you need to have at all times.

00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:36.670
And you add a few fresh ingredients and then
you've got a real meal.

00:03:36.670 --> 00:03:39.690
So, sort of basics for setting up your pantry.

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:45.459
I've also got how to set up a budget bar,
how to create a basic shopping list, that

00:03:45.459 --> 00:03:46.630
kind of stuff.

00:03:46.630 --> 00:03:51.709
And I think it's really great for people who
are just starting or, as I said, people who

00:03:51.709 --> 00:03:53.720
are trying to streamline their cooking.

00:03:53.720 --> 00:04:01.670
So, today I'm going to be making one of my
favorite appetizers, Vietnamese spring rolls

00:04:01.670 --> 00:04:02.730
with peanut sauce.

00:04:02.730 --> 00:04:05.590
I'm doing a vegetarian version.

00:04:05.590 --> 00:04:07.620
But this is one of those things that is so
cheap.

00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:11.950
Especially if you live near a good Asian specialty
grocery store.

00:04:11.950 --> 00:04:17.540
You could find everything involved so inexpensively.

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:23.009
And it's one of those things that people take
a bite of and they're so impressed with you.

00:04:23.009 --> 00:04:24.400
And that's the other piece of it.

00:04:24.400 --> 00:04:28.810
I really like getting credit for things that
weren't that hard to do.

00:04:28.810 --> 00:04:33.010
And this is a really good example of that.

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:36.710
So, anyway, we're gonna get started.

00:04:36.710 --> 00:04:43.570
And the peanut sauce for the record is one
of the yummiest things you can make.

00:04:43.570 --> 00:04:48.620
I like to make a big thing of it in the beginning
of the week and just use it in lots of different

00:04:48.620 --> 00:04:49.620
ways.

00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:52.620
I'll pour it over noodles, vegetables.

00:04:52.620 --> 00:04:55.330
It's really good over grilled salmon.

00:04:55.330 --> 00:04:57.080
It's great as a dip with crudités.

00:04:57.080 --> 00:05:04.020
You know, cut up some carrots and celery,
bell peppers and just serve it like that.

00:05:04.020 --> 00:05:09.560
And the spring rolls are basically the perfect
accompaniment for it.

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:11.650
So, I'm gonna get started.

00:05:11.650 --> 00:05:18.030
And they are a few ingredients here that you
can take or leave or swap out for something

00:05:18.030 --> 00:05:19.030
different.

00:05:19.030 --> 00:05:22.070
So, for example, I love cilantro, but I know
not everyone does.

00:05:22.070 --> 00:05:28.370
So, if you don't love cilantro, you can either
skip it, you could use finely chopped scallions

00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:30.810
or chives, or even a little flat leaf parsley.

00:05:30.810 --> 00:05:32.690
Give it a nice kick.

00:05:32.690 --> 00:05:34.580
But I'm gonna use it today.

00:05:34.580 --> 00:05:38.450
And the other thing that some people don't
love is the Sriracha.

00:05:38.450 --> 00:05:43.730
So, if you're not a spicy person, just skip
it.

00:05:43.730 --> 00:05:47.470
So, I'm starting with just some basic creamy
peanut butter.

00:05:47.470 --> 00:05:54.389
[clanking noise] The recipe is obviously in
the book so I'm not gonna talk about amounts.

00:05:54.389 --> 00:05:57.840
[clanking noise] Peanut butter is a pantry
ingredient.

00:05:57.840 --> 00:06:03.320
Something I include on the 50 dollar pantry
list because it is one of those things that

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:08.550
is relatively inexpensive, it's high protein,
and it can be used a whole bunch of different

00:06:08.550 --> 00:06:09.550
ways.

00:06:09.550 --> 00:06:11.000
So, that's there.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.751
[clanking noise] This is coconut milk.

00:06:13.751 --> 00:06:15.910
Coconut milk comes in a can.

00:06:15.910 --> 00:06:16.910
It's not very expensive.

00:06:16.910 --> 00:06:23.740
[mixing noise] I highly recommend buying the
kinds that are imported from Thailand or Vietnam.

00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:25.230
But any kind will work.

00:06:25.230 --> 00:06:28.830
I don't like to use light coconut milk because
I find it to be too watery.

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:31.600
But if that's your preference then it can
certainly be substituted.

00:06:31.600 --> 00:06:37.600
[dish clanging] And this is gonna give the
peanut sauce a really creamy consistency and

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:43.330
it's gonna blend with the peanut butter to
make a really nice base for the sauce.

00:06:43.330 --> 00:06:48.080
Then I've got some honey.

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:49.080
And my--.

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:53.600
I call for honey in this recipe but brown
sugar would also work.

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:55.940
Even white sugar, agave nectar.

00:06:55.940 --> 00:07:05.330
If you're avoiding sugar then something like
Splenda would work or stevia.

00:07:05.330 --> 00:07:07.110
It's really important to balance flavors.

00:07:07.110 --> 00:07:09.169
So, we've got some sweet.

00:07:09.169 --> 00:07:11.250
We've got, the peanut butter's a little bit
savory.

00:07:11.250 --> 00:07:13.210
We're gonna have some more savory things.

00:07:13.210 --> 00:07:15.460
This is some fresh lime juice.

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:21.510
And limes are so cheap I really recommend
against buying the bottled kind.

00:07:21.510 --> 00:07:25.780
It's so much better to just get a fresh lime.

00:07:25.780 --> 00:07:32.150
And this is gonna add some of the tartness
to the sauce.

00:07:32.150 --> 00:07:39.090
And then, I would say, maybe 95 percent of
good savory food requires garlic.

00:07:39.090 --> 00:07:41.979
So of course we're gonna get that in there.

00:07:41.979 --> 00:07:45.320
I've also got some rice vinegar.

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:49.639
If you were making this and you didn't have
rice vinegar, you could add an extra lime.

00:07:49.639 --> 00:07:50.840
You could add a little white vinegar.

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:55.410
I would recommend against balsamic 'cause
it's a little too heavy in flavor.

00:07:55.410 --> 00:07:56.860
But any sort of white vinegar.

00:07:56.860 --> 00:08:03.270
I have made it it with champagne vinegar or
even white balsamic will work in a pinch.

00:08:03.270 --> 00:08:10.270
Alright, then I've got some soy sauce which
is another important pantry ingredient.

00:08:10.270 --> 00:08:15.900
Soy sauce helps take care of that umami flavor.

00:08:15.900 --> 00:08:21.130
And it just brings a lot of that depth of
flavor without costing a whole lot.

00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:22.130
[coughing]

00:08:22.130 --> 00:08:24.370
I've also got some fresh ginger.

00:08:24.370 --> 00:08:36.139
A really important principle of BrokeAss cooking
is to use fresh, fresh things like herbs and

00:08:36.139 --> 00:08:37.169
spice.

00:08:37.169 --> 00:08:44.330
Because a container of dry ginger first of
all, won't provide much of an impact of flavor.

00:08:44.330 --> 00:08:49.089
And it will cost a lot more than buying a
big chunk of fresh ginger.

00:08:49.089 --> 00:08:52.149
So, this, I think, is much more worth it.

00:08:52.149 --> 00:08:55.790
We're gonna get that in.

00:08:55.790 --> 00:08:58.699
OK.

00:08:58.699 --> 00:09:02.279
And then I got some Sriracha.

00:09:02.279 --> 00:09:04.850
You could also use something like Sambal.

00:09:04.850 --> 00:09:06.380
Any sort of Asian chili sauce.

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:08.350
I've even done it before with Tabasco.

00:09:08.350 --> 00:09:11.600
You just want to get some fire in there.

00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:16.839
Even fresh jalapeños will work.

00:09:16.839 --> 00:09:20.860
And it's really easy.

00:09:20.860 --> 00:09:22.860
Just put this on.

00:09:22.860 --> 00:09:25.610
And it's gonna be a little loud.

