00:17:11.790 --> 00:17:14.820
But I have a lot of respect for it.

00:17:14.820 --> 00:17:19.360
Maybe do something fancy like that.

00:17:19.360 --> 00:17:23.520
And for just a few bucks you have a really
cool, easy appetizer.

00:17:23.520 --> 00:17:24.520
[applause]

00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:26.300
Thank you.

00:17:26.300 --> 00:17:31.640
&gt;&gt;male #3: Could you list a few of the other
things that are on your 50 dollar--.

00:17:31.640 --> 00:17:33.290
Things you should have in your pantry list.

00:17:33.290 --> 00:17:34.412
&gt;&gt;Gabi Moskowitz: Do I have the list?

00:17:34.412 --> 00:17:35.412
&gt;&gt; male #3: Yeah.

00:17:35.412 --> 00:17:37.190
Can you name a few of the other ones besides--.

00:17:37.190 --> 00:17:38.450
&gt;&gt;Gabi Moskowitz: Yeah.

00:17:38.450 --> 00:17:39.450
Sure.

00:17:39.450 --> 00:17:41.670
All-purpose flour, extra virgin olive oil.

00:17:41.670 --> 00:17:47.670
And in the book I actually talk about some
of the extra virgin olive oils that are a

00:17:47.670 --> 00:17:49.430
good bargain out there.

00:17:49.430 --> 00:17:55.860
Because I really don't think, I really don't
think you should be buying crappy bleached

00:17:55.860 --> 00:17:59.890
flour or bottom of the barrel olive oil.

00:17:59.890 --> 00:18:04.600
I think that you should be buying quality
things.

00:18:04.600 --> 00:18:05.730
But you don't have to spend a lot of money.

00:18:05.730 --> 00:18:08.360
So, I include some tips on that.

00:18:08.360 --> 00:18:13.270
Things like baking powder, baking soda, and
kosher salt, and black pepper.

00:18:13.270 --> 00:18:16.080
Things that you'd be really surprised a lot
of people don't think of.

00:18:16.080 --> 00:18:18.660
Those are some of the basics.

00:18:18.660 --> 00:18:22.220
Let's see, mayonnaise is another great one.

00:18:22.220 --> 00:18:27.290
Because a cool trick to do with mayonnaise
is to make a quick aioli with a variety of

00:18:27.290 --> 00:18:28.290
things.

00:18:28.290 --> 00:18:31.910
Just toss it in a blender or even whisk it
together with some chopped garlic and a little

00:18:31.910 --> 00:18:33.230
lemon juice and salt and pepper.

00:18:33.230 --> 00:18:38.660
Or my favorite is mayonnaise and Sriracha
together.

00:18:38.660 --> 00:18:43.030
Eat it with sweet potato fries and it's unbelievable.

00:18:43.030 --> 00:18:44.269
Those are some examples.

00:18:44.269 --> 00:18:48.300
&gt;&gt; male #4: Where do you get the inspiration
for your recipes?

00:18:48.300 --> 00:18:49.970
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: My inspiration?

00:18:49.970 --> 00:18:53.000
So, I live in San Francisco in the Mission
District.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:19:02.760
I don't know if anyone knows that area but
it's turned into a culinary mecca slash ghetto.

00:19:02.760 --> 00:19:04.610
[laughs] It's awesome.

00:19:04.610 --> 00:19:08.610
I live right by Delores Park and 18th street.

00:19:08.610 --> 00:19:09.610
There's this--.

00:19:09.610 --> 00:19:12.370
There's just restaurant after restaurant.

00:19:12.370 --> 00:19:13.740
Full of inspiration.

00:19:13.740 --> 00:19:19.630
So, one of my favorite things to do is to
go during happy hour when a lot of times small

00:19:19.630 --> 00:19:24.000
plates are offered at a reduced price.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.860
And taste things and get inspiration.

00:19:26.860 --> 00:19:28.760
I'll make notes.

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:34.100
And I also read other blogs constantly and
cookbooks.

00:19:34.100 --> 00:19:37.690
I watch not that much food TV.

00:19:37.690 --> 00:19:39.830
I'm not really that into reality television.

00:19:39.830 --> 00:19:45.700
But I do love watching things like Iron Chef
sometimes you can get a lot of ideas there.

00:19:45.700 --> 00:19:47.640
But mostly from restaurants.

00:19:47.640 --> 00:19:51.290
&gt;&gt; male #5: What are your top five restaurants
in Los Angeles?

00:19:51.290 --> 00:19:52.980
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: I don't know.

00:19:52.980 --> 00:19:55.190
[laughs] I don't know.

00:19:55.190 --> 00:19:56.190
I love--.

00:19:56.190 --> 00:19:59.560
There's this place, I think it's around here
called Gialina.

00:19:59.560 --> 00:20:01.370
An Italian spot.

00:20:01.370 --> 00:20:02.600
Gialina.

00:20:02.600 --> 00:20:03.910
That's great.

00:20:03.910 --> 00:20:06.770
I really don't know the L.A. restaurant scene.

00:20:06.770 --> 00:20:07.770
I could tell you--.

00:20:07.770 --> 00:20:09.550
&gt;&gt; male #5: What about San Francisco?

00:20:09.550 --> 00:20:12.230
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: San Francisco, OK.

00:20:12.230 --> 00:20:19.140
Let's see, there was this wonderful Pakistani
restaurant that just closed called, Lahore

00:20:19.140 --> 00:20:21.000
Karahi.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.150
But the guy who owned it is going to be opening
up another one.

00:20:23.150 --> 00:20:31.600
And it was this hole in the wall but for nine
or ten dollars a person you could eat incredibly

00:20:31.600 --> 00:20:33.730
well.

00:20:33.730 --> 00:20:39.740
I live very close to a great restaurant called
Delfina on 18th street,

00:20:39.740 --> 00:20:40.740
[coughing]

00:20:40.740 --> 00:20:41.740
In San Francisco.

00:20:41.740 --> 00:20:43.850
And it is outrageous and it has amazing pizza.

00:20:43.850 --> 00:20:44.850
We're sort of--.

00:20:44.850 --> 00:20:47.200
There's a big pizza trend right now in San
Francisco.

00:20:47.200 --> 00:20:51.190
Everybody's trying to outdo each other with
wood burning pizza.

00:20:51.190 --> 00:20:53.640
Wood burning stove pizza.

00:20:53.640 --> 00:21:00.990
So, that's definitely up there.

00:21:00.990 --> 00:21:06.080
There's this sushi spot at 16th and Valencia
in San Francisco called, Sushi Yo-Yo.

00:21:06.080 --> 00:21:12.200
And it's another one of those magical gems
where you can get incredibly fresh fish, really

00:21:12.200 --> 00:21:17.450
innovative rolls, and things like that for
not a lot of money.

00:21:17.450 --> 00:21:20.300
It doesn't look like much, but you go in and
it's great.

00:21:20.300 --> 00:21:27.640
One of my favorite gastro pubs is this place
called The Monk's Kettle.

00:21:27.640 --> 00:21:30.870
That's an awesome spot.

00:21:30.870 --> 00:21:40.620
And-- Oh and then there's this nameless dim-sum
place on Clemens Street.

00:21:40.620 --> 00:21:44.380
I don't know what it's called, but it's directly
across the street from Green Apple Books.

00:21:44.380 --> 00:21:47.270
&gt;&gt; male #6: First of all you've ruined peanut
sauce.

00:21:47.270 --> 00:21:48.490
It was the best kept secret.

00:21:48.490 --> 00:21:50.000
It's so easy to make and now everybody knows
about it.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:51.000
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: Awesome.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:52.920
&gt;&gt; male #6: That was like my favorite go to.

00:21:52.920 --> 00:21:54.990
Now the secret's out.

00:21:54.990 --> 00:22:00.000
So, I love cooking and one thing that I just
can't master is making my own pizza dough.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:01.000
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: Oh.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.320
&gt;&gt; male #6: Do you have a kitchen nemesis
that you just can't--.

00:22:03.320 --> 00:22:04.320
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: No.

00:22:04.320 --> 00:22:05.320
OK.

00:22:05.320 --> 00:22:08.310
Well first of all I have a second book coming
out and it's all about things to do with pizza

00:22:08.310 --> 00:22:09.310
dough.

00:22:09.310 --> 00:22:11.881
You should check out my pizza dough recipe
because it's awesome.

00:22:11.881 --> 00:22:18.270
It really is, I get that it's tricky but I
have a really simple recipe.

00:22:18.270 --> 00:22:19.350
Check it out.

00:22:19.350 --> 00:22:20.390
So, that's the first thing.

00:22:20.390 --> 00:22:22.690
Do I have a kitchen nemesis?

00:22:22.690 --> 00:22:27.180
I did and you can read about it in the book.

00:22:27.180 --> 00:22:33.770
It took me a really long time to get homemade
mayonnaise down.

00:22:33.770 --> 00:22:38.850
And so, I tell a story in the book, I don't
think I include this detail which I'm about

00:22:38.850 --> 00:22:45.000
to share which is that, the most, well, not
the most recent time I made it.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:51.500
But I tell a particular story about a time
when, it was like a week after I had been

00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:57.990
unceremoniously dumped, and I 'm standing
in my kitchen and I'm making, I'm trying to

00:22:57.990 --> 00:23:02.020
make aioli for my blog.

00:23:02.020 --> 00:23:06.830
'Cause I'm trying to distract myself with
work and it's not working and it looks just

00:23:06.830 --> 00:23:08.760
like it had every other time I made it.

00:23:08.760 --> 00:23:14.710
A useless pile of oil and eggs with a few
drops of vinegar.

00:23:14.710 --> 00:23:20.710
But the cool thing about when you have a kitchen
nemesis, which I have learned, is that you

00:23:20.710 --> 00:23:24.580
can Google whatever it is you're trying to
make.

00:23:24.580 --> 00:23:27.180
Thanks for that by the way guys, I really
appreciate it.

00:23:27.180 --> 00:23:28.180
[laughter]

00:23:28.180 --> 00:23:29.240
And there are forums.

00:23:29.240 --> 00:23:30.490
There are forums on everything.

00:23:30.490 --> 00:23:34.450
So, I bet if you search 'trouble with pizza
dough'.

00:23:34.450 --> 00:23:41.120
I bet you will find a whole group of supportive
people who you can talk about your troubles

00:23:41.120 --> 00:23:42.120
with pizza dough.

00:23:42.120 --> 00:23:44.970
But you can also get some suggestions.

00:23:44.970 --> 00:23:52.340
So, the thing I learned from looking up mayonnaise
is that if you add few--.

00:23:52.340 --> 00:23:55.910
If your mayonnaise breaks, which is what it's
called when it falls apart, it just looks

00:23:55.910 --> 00:23:57.250
like eggs and oil.

00:23:57.250 --> 00:23:59.030
Doesn't look like anything else.

00:23:59.030 --> 00:24:03.070
You slowly add drop by drop a little bit of
water.

00:24:03.070 --> 00:24:05.630
And you whisk and whisk and whisk and it brings
it back to life.

00:24:05.630 --> 00:24:09.550
And it fixed it and I felt a lot better.

00:24:09.550 --> 00:24:11.510
And I bet there's a solution with pizza dough.

00:24:11.510 --> 00:24:15.440
While we're talking about pizza dough can
you tell me what goes wrong?

00:24:15.440 --> 00:24:21.330
&gt;&gt;male #6: It usually just ends up bready
than pizza doughy.

00:24:21.330 --> 00:24:22.870
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: More bready than pizza
doughy?

00:24:22.870 --> 00:24:23.870
&gt;&gt; male #6: Yeah.

00:24:23.870 --> 00:24:24.870
It's like it's too thick.

00:24:24.870 --> 00:24:25.870
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: OK.

00:24:25.870 --> 00:24:26.870
&gt;&gt; male #6: It's not like New York pizza.

00:24:26.870 --> 00:24:28.000
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: Here's the deal.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:31.900
So, first of all you may be using a little
too much flour.

00:24:31.900 --> 00:24:38.170
The other thing is the difference between
a puffy piece of white dough, bread dough,

00:24:38.170 --> 00:24:39.410
or bread.

00:24:39.410 --> 00:24:41.990
And then pizza dough is that there's more
gluten in pizza dough.

00:24:41.990 --> 00:24:44.630
I know where in a war on gluten or something
right now.

00:24:44.630 --> 00:24:50.220
But you need to probably knead it more or
leave it in your stand up mixer for longer

00:24:50.220 --> 00:24:51.220
because--.

00:24:51.220 --> 00:24:52.651
&gt;&gt; male #6: I've tried everything.

00:24:52.651 --> 00:24:53.651
I've done it by hand.

00:24:53.651 --> 00:24:54.651
I've done it in the Kitchen Aide mixer.

00:24:54.651 --> 00:24:55.651
I brought a bread maker.

00:24:55.651 --> 00:24:56.651
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: Oh.

00:24:56.651 --> 00:24:57.651
&gt;&gt; male #6: It's just I am not able to slay
this dragon.

00:24:57.651 --> 00:25:00.280
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: Well, you should try my
recipe for sure.

00:25:00.280 --> 00:25:01.280
[laughter]

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:06.310
I mean, really, I read is the thing I hear
most from people that it works from them.

00:25:06.310 --> 00:25:07.340
So, that's one.

00:25:07.340 --> 00:25:13.080
But the other thing is that maybe, or even
if it's not my recipe, maybe try a few different

00:25:13.080 --> 00:25:14.080
recipes.

00:25:14.080 --> 00:25:15.080
Where--.

00:25:15.080 --> 00:25:16.080
Which recipe are you using?

00:25:16.080 --> 00:25:17.080
&gt;&gt; male #6: Again, all.

00:25:17.080 --> 00:25:18.080
[laughs]

00:25:18.080 --> 00:25:19.080
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: All?

00:25:19.080 --> 00:25:20.080
&gt;&gt; male #6: Yeah I just go online and you
know.

00:25:20.080 --> 00:25:21.080
But.

00:25:21.080 --> 00:25:22.860
Unfortunately I'm trying to duplicate a New
York style pizza.

00:25:22.860 --> 00:25:23.860
Which is probably--

00:25:23.860 --> 00:25:24.860
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: OK.

00:25:24.860 --> 00:25:25.860
&gt;&gt; male #6: I think that's pretty--.

00:25:25.860 --> 00:25:26.860
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: Well here's another thing
to think about.

00:25:26.860 --> 00:25:31.250
You may not be rolling it out thinly enough
when you bake the pizza.

00:25:31.250 --> 00:25:32.250
Because they--.

00:25:32.250 --> 00:25:38.680
You ever watch them in pizza restaurants they
roll them out, it's like super thin.

00:25:38.680 --> 00:25:41.470
Because there's yeast in it, it puffs up a
little bit.

00:25:41.470 --> 00:25:43.169
So, that may be an issue.

00:25:43.169 --> 00:25:44.270
&gt;&gt; male #6: How long do you let yours rest?

00:25:44.270 --> 00:25:45.270
Is it-- can you make it the same day?

00:25:45.270 --> 00:25:46.270
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: What's that?

00:25:46.270 --> 00:25:49.250
&gt;&gt; male #6: Do you really let it set overnight
or do you--.

00:25:49.250 --> 00:25:50.720
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: Oh no, no, no.

00:25:50.720 --> 00:25:52.640
I only do a short rise.

00:25:52.640 --> 00:25:58.750
I'll do two short rises like two 25 to 30
minute short rises and that seems to work.

00:25:58.750 --> 00:26:07.140
It is kind of cool to, after you've made it,
put it in a oiled Ziploc bag and leave it

00:26:07.140 --> 00:26:08.680
in the fridge.

00:26:08.680 --> 00:26:12.650
And what happens is the flavor develops over
time so that's really great.

00:26:12.650 --> 00:26:18.650
Another good trick to make it thin without
breaking it is to take a bowl like this and

00:26:18.650 --> 00:26:24.850
flip it over and lightly flour it and put
your stretched out dough on top.

00:26:24.850 --> 00:26:29.701
Which will help it maintain its shape and
keep it thin without breaking it.

00:26:29.701 --> 00:26:33.680
'Cause it can be sort of hard to pull when
you pull by hand.

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:36.100
&gt;&gt;male #6: Is there an 800 help line?

00:26:36.100 --> 00:26:38.700
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: [laughs] it’s a 900 line
actually.

00:26:38.700 --> 00:26:39.700
[laughter]

00:26:39.700 --> 00:26:44.960
&gt;&gt; male presenter: I was hoping you could
talk a little bit about your experience actually

00:26:44.960 --> 00:26:50.710
starting your blog and working with your blog
and using social media to promote it.

00:26:50.710 --> 00:26:52.120
&gt;&gt; Gabi Moskowitz: Sure.

00:26:52.120 --> 00:26:53.120
Sure.

00:26:53.120 --> 00:26:56.350
So, I did not plan to be a food blogger.

00:26:56.350 --> 00:26:58.990
It was not the game plan.

00:26:58.990 --> 00:27:04.350
I got a degree from Emerson College in Theater
Education.

00:27:04.350 --> 00:27:09.010
Got a job right out of college teaching kindergarten.

00:27:09.010 --> 00:27:10.010
And it was great.

00:27:10.010 --> 00:27:11.120
It was really fun.

00:27:11.120 --> 00:27:16.720
And after about three years, I got to a point
where I started to feel like maybe wasn't

00:27:16.720 --> 00:27:19.950
what I wanted to do for the rest of my life.

00:27:19.950 --> 00:27:24.080
So, I started thinking about what it is I
did want to do.

00:27:24.080 --> 00:27:25.080
And I--.

00:27:25.080 --> 00:27:30.080
One of my favorite things to do in the classroom
had been cooking with the kids.

00:27:30.080 --> 00:27:34.100
Because it was a great way to teach reading.

00:27:34.100 --> 00:27:35.470
I'd have them read the recipes.

00:27:35.470 --> 00:27:38.880
Science, we’d talk about how yeast works,
how baking soda works.

00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:40.930
Things like that.

00:27:40.930 --> 00:27:45.790
And math because there's if we were doubling
the recipe they'd have to figure that out.

00:27:45.790 --> 00:27:46.790
And sharing.

00:27:46.790 --> 00:27:51.120
And also a greater understanding of where
food comes from and what goes into cooking

00:27:51.120 --> 00:27:53.430
and buying food and things like that.

00:27:53.430 --> 00:27:57.950
So, and I did wanna continue teaching in some
way.

00:27:57.950 --> 00:28:04.770
So, I kind of started, it was a funny idea
that developed into an actual business.

00:28:04.770 --> 00:28:06.720
This catering business.

00:28:06.720 --> 00:28:09.940
I would cater parties and I would also do
a lot of teaching.

00:28:09.940 --> 00:28:14.880
I would teach people how to cook basic things.

00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:16.670
I would do cooking classes for kids.

00:28:16.670 --> 00:28:18.170
I would do cooking parties.

00:28:18.170 --> 00:28:23.280
And it was really fun and much more lucrative
than teaching.

00:28:23.280 --> 00:28:24.820
And it was great.

00:28:24.820 --> 00:28:27.600
And that was going OK.

00:28:27.600 --> 00:28:35.610
And then a friend of mine and I started talking
about this trend we were noticing where all

00:28:35.610 --> 00:28:39.950
our friends were having a hard time managing
to feed themselves well.

00:28:39.950 --> 00:28:41.850
So, we--.

00:28:41.850 --> 00:28:46.890
I had been writing a BlogSpot blog and it
was called, “out of the pantry."

00:28:46.890 --> 00:28:47.940
It's still up there.

00:28:47.940 --> 00:28:49.780
Gabi Moskowitz dot com.

00:28:49.780 --> 00:28:56.180
And it was like it a combination of personal
stories and recipes and drawing comparison

00:28:56.180 --> 00:28:59.630
between cooking and personal stories and things
like that.

00:28:59.630 --> 00:29:08.080
And so I made the leap into blogging solely
about food.

00:29:08.080 --> 00:29:16.510
And to my utter shock and surprise, two weeks
after I launched, MSN Money ran a story about

00:29:16.510 --> 00:29:17.510
us.

00:29:17.510 --> 00:29:26.480
And all of a sudden we went from a few hundred
hits to 30 thousand overnight for a week or

00:29:26.480 --> 00:29:27.480
so.

00:29:27.480 --> 00:29:33.240
And so I very quickly determined that I needed
to monetize this thing and I managed to get

00:29:33.240 --> 00:29:34.240
some ads.

00:29:34.240 --> 00:29:37.310
I work with SAY Media who are fantastic.

00:29:37.310 --> 00:29:40.300
And I also got syndicated.

00:29:40.300 --> 00:29:47.620
So, there are a variety of newspapers and
websites and magazines that run my content

00:29:47.620 --> 00:29:49.010
regularly.

00:29:49.010 --> 00:29:55.380
And it took about a year, but I got to a point
where I could leave my day job and blog full

00:29:55.380 --> 00:29:56.380
time.

00:29:56.380 --> 00:30:06.970
And in January of 2011, yeah 2011, a publishing
house, Egg and Dart, reached out to me and

00:30:06.970 --> 00:30:09.370
offered me a book deal.

00:30:09.370 --> 00:30:16.440
So, I feel unbelievably fortunate to get to
do the thing I love the most for a living.

00:30:16.440 --> 00:30:19.250
And it's thrilling and tons of fun.

00:30:19.250 --> 00:30:20.250
And it's--.

00:30:20.250 --> 00:30:23.400
I can't wait to find out what's gonna happen
next.

00:30:23.400 --> 00:30:25.650
So, that's sort of the journey.

00:30:25.650 --> 00:30:27.310
&gt;&gt; male #7: Hi.

00:30:27.310 --> 00:30:30.900
So, my question is more about tools in the
kitchen.

00:30:30.900 --> 00:30:33.760
So, you've talked a lot about the ingredients
you put into your food but for somebody that's

00:30:33.760 --> 00:30:35.920
a beginner cook, they probably need to know
how to have things like knives, cutting boards.

00:30:35.920 --> 00:30:42.710
